@page "/how-it-works"
@attribute [AllowAnonymous]

<PageMeta Title="How ScamAlert works — Windows remote-access alerts"
          Description="Subscribe, install on your Windows PC, add alert contacts, and get SMS when suspicious remote access is detected."
          CanonicalPath="/how-it-works" />

<h1 class="h3 mb-3">How ScamAlert works</h1>
<p class="lead text-secondary">
    ScamAlert is a <strong>single-user license</strong> that watches remote-access paths on the Windows PCs you register.
</p>

<div class="row g-4 mb-5">
    <div class="col-lg-8">
        <ol class="sa-steps">
            <li>
                <strong>Create your account.</strong>
                Sign up for the $7.99/month license and add the contacts who should receive alerts.
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>Install on your PC.</strong>
                Download the Windows app, run the pairing wizard, and link the machine from your dashboard.
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>We watch remote-access paths.</strong>
                When inbound RDP, SSH, or Telnet activity looks like an access attempt, the PC records it and your account is notified.
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>Your contacts get SMS.</strong>
                Texts go to numbers you provide—not our staff. If the first person does not respond, we can escalate to the next contact you listed.
            </li>
            <li>
                <strong>You decide what to do.</strong>
                Verify whether you expected access, hang up on scammers, or secure the machine.
            </li>
        </ol>
    </div>
    <div class="col-lg-4">
        <div class="card">
            <div class="card-body">
                <h2 class="h6">What we are (and are not)</h2>
                <ul class="small text-secondary mb-0">
                    <li class="mb-2"><strong>We are</strong> an early-warning layer for remote access on PCs you choose.</li>
                    <li class="mb-2"><strong>We are not</strong> antivirus, a VPN, or a guarantee that scams will never succeed.</li>
                    <li class="mb-2"><strong>We are not</strong> a service that reads your email or browses your files.</li>
                </ul>
            </div>
        </div>
    </div>
</div>

<div class="sa-muted-panel rounded p-4 mb-4">
    <h2 class="h5">Why people use ScamAlert</h2>
    <p class="text-secondary mb-0">
        Refund scams and fake tech support often end with “install this so we can help.” ScamAlert gives you a chance to
        <em>notice and respond</em> when remote access shows up—before a session turns into drained accounts or gift cards.
    </p>
</div>

<p class="mb-0">
    <a class="btn btn-primary me-2" href="/signup">Get started</a>
    <a class="btn btn-outline-secondary" href="/faq">Read FAQ</a>
</p>
